From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jerome Laban <noreply@platform.uno>
Date: Tue, 12 May 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fix: interpreter fallback when gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper
 is missing in aot-only mode

The AOT-side widening in patch 0007 closes the gsharedvt_out_sig
coverage gap for signatures observed during compilation
(cfg->signatures and cfg->interp_in_signatures). It cannot help
signatures the AOT compiler never observed at compile time — for
example signatures synthesised by the interpreter at runtime from
method metadata.

A concrete instance from a WASM worker hosting Roslyn (.NET 10):

  [MONO] * Assertion at .../mono/mini/interp/interp.c,
    function: init_jit_call_info,
    Attempting to JIT compile method '(wrapper other) void object:
      gsharedvt_out_sig (intptr,
        Microsoft.CodeAnalysis.CompoundUseSiteInfo`1<object>&,
        object&, object&, intptr)'
    while running in aot-only mode.

Symbol scan of the AOT-built worker wasm confirms: with patch 0007
applied, IN wrappers for 9 CompoundUseSiteInfo<object>-bearing
signatures are present, but the failing 5-param shape itself appears
in NEITHER the IN nor the OUT direction. No widening loop can catch
it because the AOT compiler never observed it.

This patch adds a runtime-side fallback. When
mono_jit_compile_method_jit_only fails on the OUT wrapper, ask the
interpreter for an entry trampoline for the WRAPPER (not the target
method) via
mini_get_interp_callbacks ()->create_method_pointer_llvmonly. That
returns a MonoFtnDesc whose .addr is a gsharedvt_in_sig wrapper for
the OUT wrapper's signature, and whose .arg is an inner ftndesc
containing the interp entry_func and the InterpMethod for the
OUT wrapper. Because the OUT wrapper's signature is all-pointer
(explicit vret + byref params + ftndesc), its IN wrapper passes the
call-site args straight through to the interpreter entry, which
then runs the OUT wrapper's IL. The IL performs the byref-deref /
box steps and calli's the underlying method through the rgctx
ftndesc.

Splice into the wrapped jit_call_cb path the same way the native
OUT wrapper would have been wired: cinfo->wrapper = IN wrapper addr;
cinfo->addr / cinfo->extra_arg = inner ftndesc. jit_call_cb assembles
{addr, extra_arg} on the stack as a MonoFtnDesc and passes it as the
final argument — matching the call shape jit_call_cb already uses
for the native wrapped path.

Why this works where a previous attempt (splicing the IN wrapper for
the TARGET method into the no_wrapper path) did NOT: the no_wrapper
path passes args sized to the target method's signature, while the
target method's IN wrapper expects a different arg count when the
gsharedvt-shaping differs. Using the OUT wrapper's IN wrapper
preserves the OUT wrapper's calling convention end-to-end.

A g_warning is logged on every fallback so silent drifts in AOT-side
wrapper coverage do not regress into a slower interpreter path
unnoticed.

Trade-offs:
- Slower than calling the AOT-compiled method through a native
  gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper. Correct, and avoids a g_assert-driven
  runtime exit.
- Requires the IN wrapper for the OUT wrapper's signature to exist
  in the AOT image. The OUT wrapper's signature is fully
  pointer-typed, so its IN wrapper is almost always present (it is
  emitted from many paths). If it is also missing,
  interp_create_method_pointer_llvmonly asserts internally — at
  that point the original abort behaviour is the floor.

Fixes: downstream WASM worker AOT path (LLVMOnly+Interp).
---
 src/mono/mono/mini/interp/interp.c | 64 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 60 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/src/mono/mono/mini/interp/interp.c b/src/mono/mono/mini/interp/interp.c
index 0a12875dcce..ad6c739a6bc 100644
--- a/src/mono/mono/mini/interp/interp.c
+++ b/src/mono/mono/mini/interp/interp.c
@@ -2731,17 +2731,73 @@ init_jit_call_info (InterpMethod *rmethod, MonoError *error)
 	}
 
 	gpointer jit_wrapper = NULL;
+	gboolean interp_fallback = FALSE;
 	if (need_wrapper) {
 		MonoMethod *wrapper = mini_get_gsharedvt_out_sig_wrapper (sig);
 		jit_wrapper = mono_jit_compile_method_jit_only (wrapper, error);
-		mono_error_assert_ok (error);
+		if (!is_ok (error)) {
+			/*
+			 * The gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper for this signature is not in the
+			 * AOT image and we cannot JIT it in aot-only mode (LLVMOnly+Interp
+			 * on WASM). This happens for signatures the AOT compiler never
+			 * observed at compile time (cfg->signatures, cfg->interp_in_signatures)
+			 * and synthesised by the interpreter at runtime from method metadata.
+			 *
+			 * Fallback: route the call through the interpreter executing the
+			 * gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper's IL. The IL does the byref-deref /
+			 * box steps and then calli's the underlying method via the rgctx
+			 * ftndesc. Interpreting it avoids the missing native wrapper.
+			 *
+			 * `interp_create_method_pointer_llvmonly (wrapper, ...)` returns a
+			 * MonoFtnDesc { addr = gsharedvt_in_sig wrapper for the OUT
+			 * wrapper's signature, arg = inner ftndesc { entry_func,
+			 * InterpMethod } }. The OUT wrapper's signature is fully
+			 * pointer-typed (vret + byref params + ftndesc), so its IN wrapper
+			 * passes the call-site args straight through to the interpreter
+			 * entry, which then runs the OUT wrapper's IL.
+			 *
+			 * Splice into the wrapped jit_call_cb path: cinfo->wrapper holds
+			 * the IN wrapper's addr; cinfo->addr / cinfo->extra_arg form the
+			 * inner ftndesc that jit_call_cb assembles and passes as the
+			 * final argument. This is the same plumbing the wrapped path
+			 * already uses for the native OUT wrapper.
+			 *
+			 * Requires: a gsharedvt_in_sig wrapper for the OUT wrapper's
+			 * signature exists in the AOT image. Because the OUT wrapper's
+			 * signature is all-pointer, this IN wrapper is almost always
+			 * present (the AOT compiler emits IN wrappers from many paths).
+			 * If it is also missing, interp_create_method_pointer_llvmonly
+			 * asserts internally — that is the floor of this fallback.
+			 *
+			 * Log a warning so future drifts in AOT-side wrapper coverage do
+			 * not silently regress into the slower interpreter path.
+			 */
+			mono_error_cleanup (error);
+			error_init (error);
+
+			MonoFtnDesc *interp_ftndesc = mini_get_interp_callbacks ()->create_method_pointer_llvmonly (wrapper, FALSE, error);
+			mono_error_assert_ok (error);
+			g_assert (interp_ftndesc);
+			MonoFtnDesc *inner = (MonoFtnDesc*)interp_ftndesc->arg;
+			g_assert (inner);
+
+			g_warning ("Falling back to interpreter for missing gsharedvt_out_sig wrapper of '%s' (signature not observed at AOT compile time).",
+				mono_method_full_name (method, TRUE));
+
+			jit_wrapper = interp_ftndesc->addr;
+			cinfo->addr = inner->addr;
+			cinfo->extra_arg = inner->arg;
+			interp_fallback = TRUE;
+		}
 	}
 
-	if (mono_llvm_only) {
-		gboolean caller_gsharedvt = !need_wrapper;
-		cinfo->addr = mini_llvmonly_add_method_wrappers (method, addr, caller_gsharedvt, FALSE, &cinfo->extra_arg);
-	} else {
-		cinfo->addr = addr;
+	if (!interp_fallback) {
+		if (mono_llvm_only) {
+			gboolean caller_gsharedvt = !need_wrapper;
+			cinfo->addr = mini_llvmonly_add_method_wrappers (method, addr, caller_gsharedvt, FALSE, &cinfo->extra_arg);
+		} else {
+			cinfo->addr = addr;
+		}
 	}
 
 	cinfo->sig = sig;
--
2.43.0
